\subsection{Why a \em{pamudpod} makes sense in \em{baybayin}}

The \em{pamudpod} is a \em{virama}. \em{Baybayin}, the local name for what The Unicode Standard calls the Tagalog script, though, already has a \em{virama} encodedâ€”\tagl{â—Œáœ”}, U+1714, \font[features=+smcp]{Tagalog Sign Virama}, known in Tagalog as the \em{krus kudlit}.

So, why another \em{virama}? Well, first of all, it's being used, as I'll demonstrate, but the use of the \em{pamudpod} makes sense and is being enthusiastically adopted by a large portion of the \em{baybayin}-using community; several subject matter experts use it in their work, such as Norman de los Santos and Kristian Kabuay.

As far as I can tell, these are some of the reasons a \em{pamudpod} is preferred by many over the currently encoded \em{krus kudlit}:


\subsection{The \em{pamudpod} is, indeed, native}

Some would say that really the \em{pamudpod} is no better as it was â€œinventedâ€ by a Dutchman, Antoon Postma, who married into the Mangyan people and studied their language, Hanuno'o, during his life. Indeed, this argument was even tried against Postma's Mangyan Cultural Center\footnote{Postma is now deceased, but he founded the organization in 2000.} by an organization who claimed â€œ\em{Surat Mangyan} (Hanuno'o) was changed to suit an anthropologist's visionâ€.\footnote{It seems that the organization who argued it, â€œTsinelas Republicâ€, recanted their statement; their \BH{\href[src=https://www.facebook.com/Tsinelas-Republic-1431559690477657/]{Facebook page}} no longer links to it, and the \BH{\href[src=http://archive.is/http://www.tsinelasrepublic.com/surat-mangyan-changed-to-suit-anthropologists-version/]{page itself}} returns an error. Internet Archive doesn't have it; all that remains is the \BH{\href[src=https://www.facebook.com/MHCOfficial/posts/thank-you-so-much-fr-ferdinand-bajao-for-taking-the-time-to-explain-so-well-post/1233467780007310/]{Mangyan Cultural Center's response.}}}

Even if this were true, it is certainly better to use a symbol originated in the independent Philippines which the Mangyan people voluntarily accepted rather than one which was forced upon the Tagalogs by a colonial dictatorship. However, it is not true; as the Mangyan Cultural Center notesâ€¦\footnote{Ibid.}

