Third party verification of this can be had by referring to \BH{\href[src=http://std.dkuug.dk/JTC1/SC2/WG2/docs/n4266.pdf]{L2/12-125}}.\footnote{Pandey, Anshuman (2012). â€œPreliminary Proposal to Encode the Kawi Scriptâ€. pp. 1.} That paper recommends the encoding of Later Kawi, the script of the Laguna Copperplate Inscription, and specifically its \em{virama} at U+11D3F.\footnote{This codepoint now contains â—Œ\kern[width=-0.3em]\raise[height=1.3ex]{\font[family=Unifont Upper]{ğ‘´¿}}\kern[width=0.3em] \font[features=+smcp]{Masaram Gondi Vowel Sign Au}.}: \img[src=kawi.png,height=2%ph]\footnote{Ibid. p. 4.}

Where then did this misunderstanding come from? It is indeed true that Postma introduced the \em{pamudpod} to the Mangyan people as part of his efforts to revitalize the Hanuno'o script. However, always the scholar, Postma was careful to borrow a construct from already existing Philippine scriptsâ€”not just simply draw a cross and call it a day.

\subsection{Why the \em{baybayin} community needs, once again, the Consortium's intervention}

Of course, it is bad on its own that a character has a misleading name which does not reflect its use in real life. And it is bad on its own that a character so routinely used in \em{baybayin} (Tagalog)\footnote{To the point where \em{pamudpod} appear multiple times in the first sentence of \BH{\href[src=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baybayin]{Wikipedia's \em{baybayin} article}}, and have done so for years.} is marked as belonging to the Hanuno'o script.

I see how this mistake happened, of course. Most other languages, especially those like Devanagari and Bengali from which the word \em{virama} originates, cannot share a \em{virama}. The very idea is absurd; they don't see the \em{virama} as a spacing mark, as Philippine script practitioners do.

And of course, due to systemic bias found in all tech, it's mostly white Europeans and Americans engaging with the Unicode Consortium. And to top it all off, before my last Tagalog proposal, \BH{\href[src=http://www.unicode.org/L2/L2019/19258r-baybayin-ra.pdf]{L2/19-258R}}, a proposal had not been made since Michael Everson's \BH{\href[src=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L1999/n1933.pdf]{L2/99-014}}. Obviously, fewer Filipinos were online then, fewer books were available (especially online), and so on.

However, due to the fact that some browsers\footnote{*cough* Chrome! *cough*} rely on Unicode's script determinations in ways I think are undue,\footnote{\BH{\href[src=https://github.com/googlefonts/noto-cjk/issues/172#issuecomment-670994063]{Perhaps an issue for the legendary Text Shaping Working Group?}}} the urgency is increased as we cannot simply work around the issue with clever OpenType tables. To explainâ€¦

Consider the sequence:

