\eject\section{On the other encoded Philippine scripts}

There are two other encoded Philippine scripts: Buhid, and Tagbanwa. Despite being on the surface similar to \em{baybayin}, they are really quite different. These other scripts are spoken by much smaller populations which are much more remote; besides Hanuno'o, their scripts are primarily of historical interest, although some modern use continues. They are not seeing modern revival on the same level \em{baybaybin} is; \em{baybayin} appears in the insignia of many large Philippine organizations, including the Armed Forces of the Philippines and the National Museum of the Philippines; it also appears on all Philippine banknotes and passports.

Nevertheless, the question was posed in an e-mail thread about this proposal as to whether the other Philippine scripts use the \em{pamudpod}. Norman de los Santos answered thus:

\line
\pullquote{
\noindent{}The late Antoon Postma, Hanunuo leaders, and the Mangyan Heritage Center (MHC) tried to introduce the use of the \em{pamudpod} mark among the Buhid but because the tribe/group is inherently aloof and their villages more remote, continued contact and education attempts were not as easy as it was with the Hanunuo.

The University of the Philippines, SIL, Mangyan Mission, and the MHC recently concluded a years long data sampling/gathering and comparative study of Buhid scripts. I was privy to the data/samples from the surveyors and their expert consultant Christopher Ray Miller. Buhid now appears to have two distinct sets of scripts. One for Bansud Buhid, and another for Bongabong-Roxas. Many CV shapes are not shared. More importantly, they do not match many of the corresponding glyph shapes represented in the Buhid Unicode range. I don't remember from whom or where the sample of Buhid Unicode typeface came from, but they are quite erroneous (if not highly stylized). The \em{pamudpod} has not been adopted by the writers. â€¦{}so there's that.

As for Palawan scripts, there are emerging Tagbanwa variants from different Tagbanwa and Palawan tribes. But documentation is sketchy, places are too remote to study, and there is no official organization that is up to the task. We are left with what we already have in Tagbanwa Unicode, which if I recall correctly, came from the book \em{Alfabeto Tagbanwa con Algunas Reformas} (\em{Tagbanwa Alphabet with Some Reforms}) by Norberto Romualdez.  As per Romualdez's reform, he has suggested an x-\em{kudlit} type \em{virama} mark that precedes the final consonant (x before the final consonant if the parent syllable has an /a/ sound, superscripted x before the final consonant if the parent syllable has an /i/ sound, and subscripted x before the final consonant if the parent syllable has an /u/ sound.) â€¦{}there's no evidence that his reforms were ever implemented beyond his book.
}
\line

In sum, right now, we only have evidence of the \em{pamudpod} being used in \em{surat Mangyan} and \em{baybayin}. The problems de los Santos mentions regarding the encoding of Buhid are a possible avenue of future work.
